#
## Table-I : Incremental memory and time data for individual events
## Short explanation of different columns follows:
## -----------------------------------------------
## Policy              --> name of the policy
## Event               --> mostly it's a rule, but in some of the cases it may refer
##                         to a particular event. e.g., SGOM population
## Lang                --> language corresponding to <Event>
##                   [VV=mixed VE=verilog VH=vhdl]
## StartPeak           --> peak memory(in KB) at the start of the <Event>
## StartHeap           --> cumulative heap memory(in KB) at the start of the <Event>
## StartMem            --> cumulative memory(in KB) at the start of the <Event>
## StartRSS            --> cumulative RSS/RAM memory(in KB) at the start of the <Event>
## StartSwap           --> cumulative Swap memory(in KB) at the start of the <Event>
## StartPeakRSS        --> Peak RSS/RAM memory(in KB) at the start of the <Event>
## IncrMem             --> memory(in KB) consumed by <Event>
## IncrHeap            --> increase in peak memory(in KB) during <Event>
## EndHeap             --> cumulative heap memory(in KB) at the end of the <Event>
## EndPeak             --> peak memory(in KB) at the end of the <Event>
## EndRSS              --> cumulative RSS/RAM memory(in KB) at the end of the <Event>
## EndSwap             --> cumulative Swap memory(in KB) at the end of the <Event>
## EndPeakRSS          --> Peak RSS/RAM memory(in KB) at the end of the <Event>
## EndPeakRSS+EndSwap  --> Peak RSS/RAM + Swap memory(in KB) at the end of the <Event>
## IncrCpuTime    --> cpu time(in seconds) taken by <Event>
## IncrClkTime    --> the elapsed time (in seconds) taken by <Event>
## Type           --> if <Event> is a rule, then it denotes 'rule-type',
##                   else it is 'NONE'
## Msg            --> mostly it'll be name of the design unit, sometimes it
##                   may denote number of design units present in the design
##
## Description: All the rows of Table-I begin with a 'i ' so that scripts
##       can filter the incremental table data and distinguish
##       them from the data of Table-II.
##
## Please note that some entries of Table-I can come after Table-II entries
## You can distinguish it with the rows begin with a 'i ' 
#---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------#
